\section{Loop equations on the gauge theory side}
\label{app:loop_eq_gt}



In this appendix, we are going to calculate the gauge theory loop equations 
using the approach of \cite{Cachazo:2002ry} \cite{Seiberg:2002jq}. 
We start with 
generalized Konishi currents and corresponding 
transformations of the fields 
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{eq: most generalized currents}
\begin{matrix}
J_f &\equiv& 
{\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} \Phi^\dagger e^{V_{\rm adj}} f (\mbox{$\cal W$}_\alpha, \Phi) 
\hfill
&
\quad
\Rightarrow 
\quad
&
\delta \Phi &=& f (\mbox{$\cal W$}_\alpha, \Phi) 
\hfill
\cr
J_g &\equiv& 
Q^\dagger_f e^{V_{\rm fund}} g_{f f'} (\Phi) Q_{f'} 
&
\quad
\Rightarrow 
\quad
&
\delta Q_{f} &=& g_{f f'} (\Phi) Q_{f'} 
\end{matrix}
\end{eqnarray} 
%for independent $f(\WW_\alpha, \Phi)$ and $g_{f f'}(\Phi)$. 
The explicitly written indices on the $Q_f$'s and $g_{f f'}$ are 
flavor indices, and gauge indices are suppressed.  
We find the generalized anomaly equations 
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{eq: generalized anomaly}
\bar D^2 J_f
&=& 
{\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} f(\mbox{$\cal W$}_\alpha , \Phi) W'(\Phi)
+
\tilde Q f(\mbox{$\cal W$}_\alpha , \Phi) m'(\Phi) Q
+
\sum_{jklm} 
A_{jk,lm} 
{\partial f_{kj}
\over
\partial \Phi_{lm} }
\nonumber\\
\bar D^2 J_g
&=& 
2 
\tilde Q m(\Phi) g(\Phi) Q
+
{\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} A^{\rm fund} g(\Phi)
\end{eqnarray}
and $\bar D^2 J_f$ and $\bar D^2 J_g$ 
vanish in the chiral ring. 


The field $\Phi$ being considered transforms by commutation 
under gauge transformations, 
so the elementary anomaly coefficient 
%\footnote{
%   In \cite{Cachazo:2002ry},
%   they have the indices $k$ and $l$ switched relative to
%   what we have in (\ref{eq: elementary anomaly coefficient}),
%   but we suspect they have a typo.
%   }
is the same as the one appearing in \cite{Cachazo:2002ry},  
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{eq: elementary anomaly coefficient}
A_{jk,lm} 
&=& 
{1 \over 32 \pi^2} 
\left[
(\mbox{$\cal W$}_\alpha \mbox{$\cal W$}^\alpha)_{jm} \delta_{lk} 
+
(\mbox{$\cal W$}_\alpha \mbox{$\cal W$}^\alpha)_{lk} \delta_{jm} 
-
2 (\mbox{$\cal W$}_\alpha)_{jm} (\mbox{$\cal W$}^\alpha)_{lk} 
\right]
\hspace{-1.5ex}
\nonumber\\
&\equiv&
{1 \over 32 \pi^2} 
\left\{
\mbox{$\cal W$}_\alpha , \left[ 
\mbox{$\cal W$}^\alpha, e_{ml} 
\right]
\right\}_{jk}
\end{eqnarray}
where $e_{ml}$ is the basis matrix with the single non-zero entry
$(e_{ml})_{jk} = \delta_{mj} \delta_{lk}$. 
%
%
For fields transforming 
in the fundamental representation we should use 
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{eq: elementary anomaly coefficient: fundamental}
A_{jk}^{\rm fund} 
&=& 
{1 \over 32 \pi^2} 
(\mbox{$\cal W$}_\alpha \mbox{$\cal W$}^\alpha)_{jk} 
\end{eqnarray}

There is one modification in the treatment of fundamental fields,
as compared to the $U(N)$ case studied in \cite{Seiberg:2002jq}.
Since the fundamental representation is real for $SO$ and
pseudo-real for $Sp$, the fields $Q$ and $\tilde Q$ are not
independent; instead, they are related by (\ref{eq:def_Qtilde}).
This results in the factor of 2 in the second equation in
(\ref{eq: generalized anomaly}), but otherwise the discussion
proceeds as in \cite{Seiberg:2002jq}. In the rest of the Appendix
we omit reference to fundamentals.





Next we consider the symmetries of $\Phi$. 
In equation (\ref{eq: most generalized currents}), 
$f = \delta \Phi$ 
must have the same symmetry properties as $\Phi$ itself. 
The tensor field will be taken either symmetric or antisymmetric.
We can discuss all four cases in a uniform fashion 
by using the notation 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Phi^T = 
\left\{
\begin{matrix}
\sigma \Phi
\hfill
&
\quad
\mbox{for groups $SO(N)$,}
\cr
\sigma J \Phi J^{-1}
&\quad
\mbox{for groups $Sp(N)$,}
\end{matrix}
\right.
\end{eqnarray}
and $\sigma = \pm 1$. 
%In the case of Sp(N), 
%the tensor is symmetric ($S^T = S$) 
%or antisymmetric $A^T = - A$), 
%and can be packaged into $\Phi = S J$ or $\Phi = A J$. 
The gauge field satisfies 
$\mbox{$\cal W$}_\alpha{}^T = - \mbox{$\cal W$}_\alpha$ for $SO$ groups, and 
$\mbox{$\cal W$}_\alpha{}^T = - J \mbox{$\cal W$}_\alpha J^{-1}$ for $Sp$ groups. 
%The superpotential is $W(\Phi)$, for either value of $\sigma$, 
%and for either type of gauge group. 
%
%
As discussed in Subsection \ref{section: loop equations}, $\Phi$
has the property \begin{eqnarray} \label{eq: projector: general} \Phi = P \Phi
,\quad\mbox{or explicitly}\quad \Phi_{ab} = P_{ab,ij} \Phi_{ij}
\end{eqnarray} with the projectors defined in (\ref{eq:def_projector}). To
ensure that $f$ has the same symmetry as $\Phi$, we should replace
$f \to P f$ in (\ref{eq: generalized anomaly}). Specifically, we
will take $\delta \Phi$ of the form \begin{eqnarray} \label{eq: delta Phi:so}
f^{SO} &=& P^{SO} {B \over z - \Phi} = \left( {B \over z - \Phi}
\right) + \sigma \left( {B \over z - \Phi} \right)^T = \left( {B
\over z - \Phi} \right) + \sigma \left( {B^T \over z - \sigma
\Phi} \right) ,
\\
\label{eq: delta Phi:sp}
f^{Sp} &=& 
P^{Sp} {B \over z - \Phi} =
\left( {B \over z - \Phi} \right) 
+ \sigma J \left( {B \over z - \Phi} \right)^T J
= 
\left( {B \over z - \Phi} \right) 
+ \sigma \left( {J B^T J \over z -\sigma \Phi} \right)
,
\end{eqnarray}
with $B = 1$ or $B = \mbox{$\cal W$}^2 \equiv \mbox{$\cal W$}_\beta \mbox{$\cal W$}^\beta$. 
Using the symmetry of the gauge field
and the chiral ring relations, 
both (\ref{eq: delta Phi:so}) and (\ref{eq: delta Phi:sp}) 
reduce to 
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{eq: delta Phi: in CR only}
f &=& 
{B \over z - \Phi}  
+ \sigma 
{B \over z - \sigma \Phi} 
.
\end{eqnarray}
%We see that indeed $f$ is a function of the matrices $\Phi$ and $\WW_\alpha$ 
%(and not of some random matrix elements of $\Phi$, say). 
%
%
Also, to take derivatives with respect to matrix elements%
\footnote{
    In the case of $U(N)$ of \cite{Cachazo:2002ry},
    one had $P_{lm,ab} = (e_{lm})_{ab}$
    which satisfies $(e_{lm})_{ab} B_{ab} = B_{lm}$, for any matrix $B$.
    }
correctly we should set 
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{eq: change of matrix elements}
\partial_{lm} \Phi_{ab} 
= 
P_{lm,ab}
\end{eqnarray}
Then the tensor field anomaly term becomes 
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{eq: anomaly: general}
A_{jk,lm} 
\; 
\partial_{lm} f_{kj}
&=& {1 \over 32 \pi^2} \left[ (\mbox{$\cal W$}^2)_{jm} \delta_{lk} +
\delta_{jm} (\mbox{$\cal W$}^2)_{lk} - 2 (\mbox{$\cal W$}_\alpha)_{jm} (\mbox{$\cal W$}^\alpha)_{lk}
\right] \nonumber\\&&\hspace{1.4em}\times \left[ \left( {B \over z
- \Phi} \right)_{ra} \left( {1 \over z - \Phi} \right)_{bs}
P_{kj,rs} P_{lm,ab} \right]. \end{eqnarray} After using the projectors
(\ref{eq:def_projector}), the identity ${\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} \mbox{$\cal W$}_\alpha \Phi^k =
0$, the symmetry properties of $\Phi$ and $\mbox{$\cal W$}_\alpha$, and the
chiral ring relations, we find \begin{eqnarray} \label{eq: anomaly: simplified}
A_{jk,lm} \;
\partial_{lm} f_{kj}
&=& {1 \over 32 \pi^2} \left[ \left( {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} {\mbox{$\cal W$}^2 \over z - \Phi}
\right) \left( {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} {B \over z - \Phi} \right) + \left( {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} {1
\over z - \Phi} \right) \left( {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} {\mbox{$\cal W$}^2 B \over z - \Phi}
\right) \right.\nonumber\\&&\left.\hspace{3em} + 4 k \sigma \; {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits}
{\mbox{$\cal W$}^2 B \over (z - \Phi) (z - \sigma \Phi)} \right] \end{eqnarray} The only
difference in (\ref{eq: anomaly: simplified}) between the two
types of gauge groups is that the sign in front of the single
trace term is $k = +1$ for $SO$, and $k = -1$ for $Sp$.
%
%
Taking $B = 1$ and $B = \mbox{$\cal W$}^2$ in (\ref{eq: anomaly: simplified}) we find 
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{eq: anomaly: simplified: B=1}
0 &=& 
{\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} { W'(\Phi) \over z - \Phi}
+ \sigma 
{\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} { W'(\Phi) \over z - \sigma \Phi}
\nonumber\\&&
+
{2 \over 32 \pi^2} 
\left[
\left( {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} {\mbox{$\cal W$}^2 \over z - \Phi} \right) 
\left( {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} {1 \over z - \Phi} \right) 
+ 2 k \sigma 
\left( {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} {\mbox{$\cal W$}^2 \over (z - \Phi)(z - \sigma \Phi)} \right) 
\right]
\\
%\ea
%If we take $B = \WW^2$, we find 
%\ba
\label{eq: anomaly: simplified: B=W-squared}
0
&=& 
{\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} { \mbox{$\cal W$}^2 W'(\Phi) \over z - \Phi}
+ \sigma 
{\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} { \mbox{$\cal W$}^2 W'(\Phi) \over z + \Phi}
%\nonumber\\&&
+ {1 \over 32 \pi^2} \left[ \left( {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} {\mbox{$\cal W$}^2 \over z - \Phi}
\right) \left( {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} {\mbox{$\cal W$}^2 \over z - \Phi} \right) \right] \end{eqnarray} Now
recall that $W(\Phi)^T = W(\Phi)$ for $SO(N)$, and $W(\Phi)^T = J
W(\Phi) J^{-1}$ for $Sp(N)$ since it only appears inside a trace;
so \begin{eqnarray} {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} { W'(\Phi) \over z -\sigma \Phi} &=& \sigma {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} {
W'(\Phi) \over z - \Phi} ,\quad {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} { \mbox{$\cal W$}^2 W'(\Phi) \over z
-\sigma \Phi} = \sigma{\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} { \mbox{$\cal W$}^2 W'(\Phi) \over z - \Phi} . \end{eqnarray}
The single trace terms have to be treated separately: when $\sigma
= -1$, \begin{eqnarray} {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} { \mbox{$\cal W$}^2 \over z^2 - \Phi^2} &=& {1\over 2 z} \; {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits}
\left[ \mbox{$\cal W$}^2 \left( { 1 \over z - \Phi} + { 1 \over z + \Phi}
\right) \right] = {1\over z} \; {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} { \mbox{$\cal W$}^2 \over z - \Phi} \end{eqnarray}
while for $\sigma = +1$, we should use \begin{eqnarray} {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} { \mbox{$\cal W$}^2 \over (z -
\Phi)^2} &=& - {d\over dz} \; {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} { \mbox{$\cal W$}^2 \over z - \Phi} . \end{eqnarray}


Putting everything together, we find the loop equations written in
equation (\ref{eq:loop_eq_gt}).




\section{Loop equations on the matrix model side}
\label{app:loop_eq_mm}


Here we derive the matrix model loop equations for $SO/Sp$
following Seiberg \cite{Seiberg:2002jq}, who discussed the $U(N)$
case.  Start with the matrix model partition function
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{eq: mm partition function}
Z = \int d {\boldsymbol{\Phi}} d {\bf Q}\,
\exp 
\left\{
- {1 \over {\bf g}} \left[
{\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits}[W({\boldsymbol{\Phi}})]
+ 
\tilde{\bf Q}_{\tilde f} m_{\tilde f f}({\boldsymbol{\Phi}}) {\bf Q}_f\right]
\right\}.
\end{eqnarray}
Because the fundamental matter is real for $SO(N)$ and pseudo-real
for $Sp(N)$, there is no integration over $\tilde{\bf Q}$.  It is not an
independent variable, but related to ${\bf Q}$ by Eq.\
(\ref{eq:def_Qtilde}).  We will write the symmetry properties of
the the tensor field ${\boldsymbol{\Phi}}$ as
\begin{eqnarray}
{\boldsymbol{\Phi}}^T = 
 \begin{cases}
  \sigma {\boldsymbol{\Phi}} & SO(N), \\
  \sigma J{\boldsymbol{\Phi}} J^{-1} & Sp(N). 
 \end{cases}
\end{eqnarray}
where $\sigma = \pm 1$.  The matrix $m({\boldsymbol{\Phi}})$ has symmetry properties as
given in Eq.\ (\ref{eq:sym_prop_m}).


Now we perform two independent transformations 
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{eq: transformations: mm}
\delta {\boldsymbol{\Phi}} = B P {1 \over z - {\boldsymbol{\Phi}}}
,\quad
\delta {\bf Q}_f = \lambda_{f f'} {1 \over z - {\boldsymbol{\Phi}}} {\bf Q}_{f'}
\end{eqnarray}
where $B$ (number) and $\lambda$ (matrix) are independent and
infinitesimal.  
To make sure that $\delta {\boldsymbol{\Phi}}$ has the same 
symmetry properties as ${\boldsymbol{\Phi}}$ itself, we have introduced 
the appropriate projector $P$ in (\ref{eq: transformations: mm}), 
see Eq.\ (\ref{eq:def_projector}).  
The measure in
(\ref{eq: mm partition function}) changes as
\begin{eqnarray}
d {\boldsymbol{\Phi}} &\to& d{\boldsymbol{\Phi}}\, J_{\boldsymbol{\Phi}} = d{\boldsymbol{\Phi}}\, (1 + \Delta_{\boldsymbol{\Phi}}),
\nonumber\\
d {\bf Q} &\to& d{\bf Q}\, J_{\bf Q} = d{\bf Q}\, (1 + \Delta_{\bf Q})
\end{eqnarray}
to first order in $B$ and $\lambda$, 
where the corresponding changes in the Jacobians are 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Delta_{\boldsymbol{\Phi}} &=& 
B 
P_{ij,ab} 
\left( {1 \over z - {\boldsymbol{\Phi}}} \right)_{ia} 
\left( {1 \over z - {\boldsymbol{\Phi}}} \right)_{bj}
\nonumber\\
\Delta_{\bf Q} &=& 
\left( {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} {1 \over z - {\boldsymbol{\Phi}}} \right)
\left( {\mathop{\mathrm{tr}}\nolimits} \lambda \right),
\end{eqnarray}
where ${\mathop{\mathrm{tr}}\nolimits}$ is a trace over the flavor indices.
The classical pieces change by 
\begin{eqnarray}
\delta \, {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits}[W({\boldsymbol{\Phi}}) ]
= B \, {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits}\left[W'({\boldsymbol{\Phi}}) P {1 \over z - {\boldsymbol{\Phi}}}\right]
= B \, {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} {W'({\boldsymbol{\Phi}}) \over z - {\boldsymbol{\Phi}}}
.
\end{eqnarray}
One can show the second equality using symmetry properties of 
$W$: since it only enters $Z$ in the form of the trace, we should 
take $W({\boldsymbol{\Phi}}^T) = W({\boldsymbol{\Phi}})$ for $SO$ and 
$W({\boldsymbol{\Phi}}^T) = J W({\boldsymbol{\Phi}}) J^{-1}$ for $Sp$. 
Similarly, 
\begin{eqnarray}
\delta ( \tilde{\bf Q} m {\bf Q} )
&=& 
\tilde{\bf Q} \left( {\lambda^T m \over z - \sigma {\boldsymbol{\Phi}}} 
+ {m \lambda \over z - {\boldsymbol{\Phi}}} \right){\bf Q} 
+ B \tilde{\bf Q} m' \left( P {1 \over z - {\boldsymbol{\Phi}}} \right) {\bf Q} 
\nonumber\\
&=&
2 \tilde{\bf Q} {m \lambda \over z - {\boldsymbol{\Phi}}} {\bf Q} 
+ B \tilde{\bf Q} {m' \over z - {\boldsymbol{\Phi}}} {\bf Q} 
,
\end{eqnarray}
where we used a similar symmetry property of the matrix $m$. 
Finally, with the explicit form of the projectors 
(\ref{eq:def_projector}) we find that in all four cases the 
statement $\delta Z = 0$ gives two independent loop equations 
(one for $B$, and one for $\lambda$): 
\begin{align}
\label{eq: exact mm loop equations}
{1\over 2}
\left\langle
\left({\bf g}
{\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} {1 \over z - {\boldsymbol{\Phi}}}
\right)^2
\right\rangle
\pm
{\sigma\over 2} {{\bf g}}
\left\langle
{{\bf g}} {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} {1 \over (z - {\boldsymbol{\Phi}})(z - \sigma {\boldsymbol{\Phi}})}
\right\rangle
&=
\left\langle
{{\bf g}} {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} {W'({\boldsymbol{\Phi}}) \over z - {\boldsymbol{\Phi}}}
\right\rangle
+ {{\bf g}}
\left\langle
\tilde{\bf Q} {m'({\boldsymbol{\Phi}}) \over z - {\boldsymbol{\Phi}}} {\bf Q}
\right\rangle,
\nonumber\\
\left\langle
{{\bf g}} {\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} {1 \over z - {\boldsymbol{\Phi}}}
\right\rangle
\delta_{ff'}
&=
2
\left\langle
\tilde{\bf Q}_{{\tilde{f}}} {m_{{\tilde{f}} f}({\boldsymbol{\Phi}})  \over z - {\boldsymbol{\Phi}}} {\bf Q}_{f'}
\right\rangle,
\end{align}
for $SO$ and 
$Sp$, respectively.
%where $\pm$ is for $SO/Sp$.  
This is Eq.\ (\ref{eq:exact_mm_loop_eqs}) 
quoted in Section \ref{section: mm loop equations}.



As it is written, equation (\ref{eq: exact mm loop equations}) 
includes all orders in ${\bf g}$. The anomaly term in the first 
equation (\ref{eq: exact mm loop equations}) factorizes as 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left\langle
\left({\bf g}
{\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} {1 \over z - {\boldsymbol{\Phi}}}
\right)^2
\right\rangle
= 
\left\langle
{\bf g}
{\mathop{\mathrm{Tr}}\nolimits} {1 \over z - {\boldsymbol{\Phi}}}
\right\rangle^2
\times \left[ 1 + {\cal O}({\bf g}^2) \right]
\end{eqnarray}
as can be seen from a diagram expansion. 
With this and the definition of matrix model resolvents 
(\ref{eq:def_mm_resolvents}) and (\ref{eq:mm_resolvents_expansion}), 
we obtain the loop equations (\ref{eq:loop_eq_mm}). 




